  <text>
    <body>
      <div subtype="original" type="letter" xml:id="L.12003" xml:lang="en">
        <pb facs="#IMG.1" n="1"/>
        <dateline>July 16 1884<note n="1" place="foot"
              type="editorial">Eigentlich Febr 16 1884. Die Neudatierung erfolgt im Hinblick auf <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.109">Schuchardts</persName> Angaben in <bibl>
              <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.bibliography#BIBL.560">
Schuchardt (1906 [= HSA 514]: 329).</ref>
            </bibl>
          </note>
          <lb/> Prof. Dr. Hugo Schuchardt:</dateline>
        <opener>Dear sir:</opener>
        <p> Your esteemed favor of the 25th ult. reached me a day or two ago, and also Dr. Schrader's<note n="2"
            place="foot" type="editorial">Vom Indogermanisten <persName
              ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.2667">Otto Schrader</persName> (1855-1919) liegen sechs Briefe an Schuchardt vor (<ref
            target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/context:hsa.letters.2667">Bibl. Nr. 10182-10287</ref>). </note> "Sprachvergleichung und Urgeschichte"<note
            n="3" place="foot" type="editorial">
            <bibl>
              <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.bibliography#BIBL.8800">Schrader (1883).</ref>
            </bibl> Schuchardt besaß davon die 2. Auflage von 1890. Das Werk ist im Katalog von Brintons Bibliothek verzeichnet (<bibl>
              <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.bibliography#BIBL.3033">Weeks 2003: 332</ref>
            </bibl>).</note>. I find this work very entertaining, as it presents an excellent review of the labors of scientific linguists in that field. Accept my thanks for it. </p>

        <p>With regard to other mixed tongues, compounds of native American and European languages, I would say that several exist, but scarcely any specimens of them have been preserved. What are called the <hi
            rend="unknown" rendition="#none">
Jarochos</hi>, of <placeName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.places#PL.5935">
Mexico</placeName>, have a Spanish-Nahuatl dialect, but I have applied in vain to my correspondents in that country for examples of it. You have no doubt seen the publications of Mr. <persName>
Geo. Gibbs</persName> on the Chinook Jargon of the North West Coast.<note
            n="4" place="foot" type="editorial">
            <bibl>
              <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.bibliography#BIBL.8780">Gibbs (1863). </ref>
            </bibl>
          </note> The <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">Lingoa geral</hi> of <placeName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.places#PL.5957">
Brazil</placeName> is in many districts a true mixture of <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.languages#L.844">Portuguese</ref> and 
Tupi. </p>
        <p>Another class of mixed languages on this <pb facs="#IMG.2"
            n="2"/>continent are the result of a mingling of European idioms. One of the most remarkable is found in the state where I live. It is the so-called "<ref
            target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.subjects#S.5532">Pennsylvania Dutch</ref>". The settlers of several of our interior counties came from the Rhenish Palatinate about 1720, &amp; their dialect has for a hundred and fifty years maintained its footing, though greatly altered. It has been especially studied by Prof. Haldeman,<note
            n="5" place="foot" type="editorial">
            <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.5531">Samuel Stehman Haldeman</persName> (1812-1880) war ab 1869 Professor für vergleichende Sprachwissenschaft an der 
University of Pennsylvania. Das gemeinte Werk ist vermutlich <bibl>
              <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.bibliography#BIBL.5315">Haldeman (1872)</ref>
            </bibl>, davon ist auch ein Exemplar in <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.subjects#S.4407">Schuchardts Bibliothek</ref> vorhanden.</note> whose work is probably known to you. </p>
        <p>You mention the <ref
            target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.languages#L.768">Spanish in Florida</ref>. It is now entirely extinct, but when I lived there in 1857 a dialect of it was still spoken. It was called the <hi
            rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">Mahonese</hi>, and was a corrupted form of the dialect of the Islands of Minorca and Majorca, whence the immigrants had been brought about a century before. I know of only one printed specimen of it, that is, the <hi
            rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">Fromajardis</hi>, or Easter Song, obtained in 1843. I have no copy in my library, but will try to find one for you. <note
            n="6" place="foot" type="editorial">Diese Passage wird in Schuchardt (1906 [= HSA 514]: 329) zitiert.</note>
        </p>

        <p> I do not contemplate publishing Dr. Berendt's MS. on the Spanish of Nicaragua, but should be willing to have it published by any learned society who desired it. <note
            n="7" place="foot" type="editorial">
            <persName>
Carl Hermann Berendt</persName> (1817-1878), deutscher Mediziner und später Mittelamerikaforscher (vgl. <bibl>
              <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.bibliography#BIBL.8801">Zimmermann 1955</ref>

            </bibl>). Brintons Bibliothek enthält zahlreiche von Berendts Manuskripten und Veröffentlichungen (vgl. Weeks 2003: 7-14). Zum Manuskript vgl. hier <ref
              target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.letter.12005">Brief 4-01377</ref> und <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.letter.12008">
7-01380</ref>.</note>
        </p>
        <p>I cannot now recall any one in this country who is making a study of your branch, but if I think of any, shall put them into relation with you. </p>
        <closer>
          <salute>I remain, Very truly yours, </salute>
          <signed>
            <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.1203">D.G. Brinton.</persName>
          </signed>
        </closer>
      </div>
